The paper deals with the problem of detecting and estimating moving targets in synthetic aperture radar (SAR) imagery, which involves complex signal processing and statistical inference. Therefore, the most likely category is computer vision (cs.CV), which deals with image analysis and understanding. Information theory (cs.IT) is also relevant, as the paper discusses the statistical properties of SAR imaging and the estimation of nuisance parameters. Control and systems engineering (cs.SY) is another possible category, as the paper proposes a hierarchical Bayesian model for SAR imaging that integrates physical and kinematic properties of the system. Machine learning (cs.LG) is also relevant, as the paper proposes a Monte Carlo method for estimating the posterior distribution of the model parameters. Finally, numerical analysis (cs.NA) is a possible category, as the paper discusses the computational aspects of the proposed algorithm.
